14. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 71072149
T1  - Life style changes versus combined oral contraceptives treatment impact on sexual life of young females with Polycystic Ovary syndrome
T3  - 1st Global Conference on Contraception, Reproductive and Sexual Health 2013. Copenhagen Denmark.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Stoian D.
A1  - Craina M.
A1  - Craciunescu M.
A1  - Anastasiu D. 
Y1  - 2013//
N2  - Objectives: Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is associated with hormonal, emotional, sexual and metabolic changes. The aim of the treatment is to restore, if possible, all above mentioned health parameters. Different approaches have positive and negative effects. Method(s): We evaluated 97 cases diagnosed with PCOS (Rotterdam criteria 2003), that were randomly assign them to one of the following subgroups: A (32 cases) - low glycemic index diet: 800 - 1000 kcal daily intake, B - COC treatment (33 cases) with Yaz preparation, C - controls (33 cases). For a period of six months we evaluated the quality of sexual life by means of the FSFI questionnaire, hormonal milieu with free testosterone (nM/L), SHBG (nM/L)DHEAS (mcg/dL), LH/FSH ratio, at base line and at the sixth month after the intervention. Result(s): There were no differences regarding age, weight or sexual activity between the study groups: Age (years): 31.15 +/- 4.5 vs 30.8 +/- 4.7 vs 31.3 +/- 3.7; BMI (kg/m 2 sc): 33.4 +/- 5.5 vs 34.01 +/- 6.7 vs 33.7 +/- 5.8; total FSFI score 21.3 +/- 1.5 vs 22.5 +/- +/- 2.8 vs 20.9 +/- 1.9. The mean weight loss in group A was 8.7 +/- 2.3 kg. The ' hormonal ' milieu of the cases did change significantly in the intervention groups: there was a decrease in free testosterone (nM/L): from 0.015 +/- 0.0016 to 0.005 +/- +/- 0,003 in weight loss group, lower than the COC group: from 0.016 +/- 0.0017 to 0.003 +/- +/- 0.001 ( p = 0.012), both significantly lower than in controls: 0.016 +/- 0.002 ( p = 0.0015, p = 0.002). LH/FSH ratio decreased in both interventional groups, and remained stable in the controls (1.75 +/- 0.15 vs 2.25 +/- 0.18 - A, 1.28 +/- +/- 0.1 vs 2.27 +/- 0.114 - B, respectively 2.28 +/- 0.113 vs 2.2.7 +/- +/- 0.0112 in controls. DHEAS decreased significantly only in the weight loss group (344.67 +/- 45.78 vs 410.64 +/- +/- 61.20). The most significant change was observed in the SHBG evolution: no change in controls: 23.05 +/- 4.87 vs 22.87 +/- 5.06, important increase in COC group: 185.51 +/- +/- 32.45 vs 24.03 +/- 5.03, normalisation in weight loss group: 64.51 +/- +/- 7.65 vs 22.90 +/- 7.06. These changes were associated with increase of FSFI domain score: sexual satisfaction, desire, arousal and orgasm score in A group, slightly increase of orgasm and sexual satisfaction scores but with decrease of arousal and desire scores in B group, with no change in controls. Conclusion(s): The intervention approach makes a difference in the hormonal and sexual quality of life in females with PCOS. Weight management has a better impact on sexual quality of life, but only in cases with sustained and significant weight change.
